[[File:Sidney Hall - Urania's Mirror - Camelopardalis, Tarandus and Custos Messium.jpg|thumb|350px|Custos Messium and the likewise-obsolete constellation of [[Rangifer (constellation)|Tarandus]] depicted above [[Camelopardalis]].]] '''Custos Messium''' ([[Latin]] for ''harvest-keeper'') was a [[constellation]] created by [[Jérôme Lalande]] in 1775 to honor [[Charles Messier]]. It was located between the constellations of [[Camelopardalis]], [[Cassiopeia (constellation)|Cassiopeia]] and [[Cepheus (constellation)|Cepheus]]. It is no longer recognized.<ref>[http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Topics/astronomy/_Texts/secondary/ALLSTA/Custos_Messium*.html Star Names-Their Lore and Meaning by Richard Hinckley Allen (1899] retrieved 22/09/2011)</ref>
