'''The Institute of Politics''' is an extracurricular, nonpartisan institute at the [[University of Chicago]] designed to inspire students to pursue careers in politics and public service.<ref>{{cite web|title=University of Chicago Institute of Politics|url=http://politics.uchicago.edu/page/about|accessdate=20 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221004703/http://politics.uchicago.edu/page/about|archive-date=21 February 2014|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref>   The Institute accomplishes its goals through four major avenues: A civic engagement program, where students take part in community service projects and gain leadership skills, a fellows program that hosts a group of political and policy professionals to lead seminars for an academic quarter, a speaker series featuring public events with a diverse array of political figures, and a career development program featuring hundreds of internships in government, politics and policy. It was formally established in 2013 with [[David Axelrod (political consultant)|David Axelrod]], who was President [[Barack Obama]]'s chief campaign advisor, as its director.<ref>{{cite news|last=Johnson|first=Dirk|title=David Axelrod on His Move to the University of Chicago|url=http://www.chicagomag.com/Chicago-Magazine/February-2013/David-Axelrod-on-His-Move-to-the-University-of-Chicago/|accessdate=20 February 2014|newspaper=Chicago Magazine|date=9 January 2013}}</ref> 

Since its inception, the IOP has hosted prominent speakers including [[Joe Biden]], [[Mitt Romney]], [[Rand Paul]], [[Al Gore]], [[Rick Santorum]], [[John McCain]], [[Newt Gingrich]], [[Bernie Sanders]], [[John O. Brennan|John Brennan]],<ref>{{cite web|title=CIA’s John Brennan talks Russia, Trump at I-House {{!}} The University of Chicago Magazine|url=https://mag.uchicago.edu/law-policy-society/cias-john-brennan-talks-russia-trump-i-house|website=mag.uchicago.edu|accessdate=January 9, 2018|language=en}}</ref> [[Frank Bruni]], [[Edward Snowden]] (via videochat), [[Jon Stewart]] and [[Chance the Rapper]]; hosted fellows such as [[Beth Myers]], [[Michael Steele]], [[Roger Simon (journalist)|Roger Simon]], [[Husain Haqqani]], [[Matthew Dowd]], [[Howard Wolfson]], [[Mark Udall]], [[Tom Harkin]], [[Michael Morell]], [[Jeff Roe]] and [[Bakari Sellers]]. It has arranged over 250 student internships to institutions like the [[U.S. Capitol]], the [[Brookings Institution]], and the [[White House]], and placed over 300 students in civic engagement projects.

